{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 22:23:18.787814", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nScope\n- Objective: Assess end-to-end health of the enterprise OSPF network fabric, with emphasis on DNS/DHCP reachability and HTTP services (web0–web3, load-balanced via web99.local).\n- Focus: Detect anomalies, localize faulty devices, identify likely root causes (no remediation proposed).\n\nSummary of Network Health\n- Control-plane (OSPF): Healthy.\n  - server_access_router has a stable Full OSPF adjacency to the core, and correctly learns/advertises 10.1.0.0/16, 10.2.0.0/16, and internal 172.16.0.x/31 links. Distribution routers also show Full OSPF neighbors and consistent routes.\n  - Server farm subnet 10.200.0.0/24 is directly attached on server_access_router (br0), and is advertised via OSPF as expected.\n- Data-plane reachability: Generally healthy.\n  - End-to-end ICMP between hosts and server farm components shows 0% packet loss with low average RTTs (few ms), though occasional single-sample spikes (e.g., 100–270 ms) were observed from some access hosts—transient and not sustained.\n- DNS resolution: Working.\n  - From hosts, getent resolves:\n    - web99.local → 10.200.0.7 (load_balancer)\n    - web0.local → 10.200.0.3, web1.local → 10.200.0.4, web2.local → 10.200.0.5, web3.local → 10.200.0.6\n- Load balancer (10.200.0.7): Reachable and listening on TCP/80. Two NICs present:\n  - eth0: 10.200.0.7/24 (default route via 10.200.0.1)\n  - eth1: 20.200.0.1/24\n\nDetected Anomalies and Localization\n\n1) Backend web server exposure to access hosts (policy violation)\n- Symptom:\n  - Access hosts can resolve and directly reach web0.local, web1.local, web2.local, web3.local (10.200.0.3–.6) via DNS and HTTP.\n- Evidence:\n  - getent hosts on access hosts returns A records for web0–web3.local pointing to 10.200.0.x.\n  - curl to web0, web2, web3 completes successfully from hosts; ICMP to all four web servers succeeds.\n- Expected design:\n  - “By design the backend web servers should not be directly accessible from the hosts.” Only web99.local (load balancer) should be the exposed endpoint.\n- Localization:\n  - dns_server is publishing web0–web3.local to the access hosts.\n  - No network ACLs/firewall on server_access_router are preventing access from user subnets to 10.200.0.0/24.\n- Likely root cause:\n  - DNS zone and/or access control misconfiguration allowing global resolution and L3 reachability to backend servers.\n\n2) Web server application failure on web_server_1 (10.200.0.4)\n- Symptom:\n  - HTTP requests to web1.local time out consistently (~5.0 s total time), despite ICMP reachability.\n- Evidence:\n  - From host_1_1_1_1: curl_web_test to http://web1.local results in 5.000–5.002 s total time for each attempt, with connect/starttransfer at 0.0—indicating the connection is made but no response body/headers are returned before timeout.\n  - From server_access_router directly to 10.200.0.4: identical ~5 s timeouts, confirming it’s not a routing issue.\n  - netstat on web_server_1 shows TCP 0.0.0.0:80 LISTEN with a non-zero Recv-Q (6), suggesting connections are piling up and not being serviced by the application.\n  - ICMP to 10.200.0.4 is normal (~3 ms), ruling out basic connectivity problems.\n- Localization:\n  - Fault is on web_server_1 host/application stack.\n- Likely root cause:\n  - HTTP service bound to port 80 is stuck/misbehaving (e.g., hung worker or application not handling requests), causing queued connections and client timeouts. This is an application-layer issue, not routing or link-layer.\n\n3) Load balancer behavior on HEAD requests\n- Symptom:\n  - HEAD to http://web99.local returns “HTTP/1.1 501 Unsupported method ('HEAD')” with Server: nginx/1.22.1.\n- Evidence:\n  - HEAD to the backend simple servers (web0, web2, web3) also yields 501 with Server: BaseHTTP/0.6 Python/3.11.2—these Python simple HTTP servers do not implement HEAD.\n  - Nginx appears to forward HEAD upstream and relay the backend’s 501 response.\n- Localization:\n  - Behavior originates from backend servers; Nginx is proxying the upstream response.\n- Likely root cause:\n  - Backends lack HEAD support; Nginx is passing through upstream 501. Not a network fault; informational.\n\n4) Minor transient latency spikes\n- Symptom:\n  - Occasional isolated ping RTT spikes (e.g., 111 ms to dns_server, 272 ms to load_balancer) from some access hosts; subsequent probes are ~2–8 ms.\n- Evidence:\n  - One-off high RTTs amidst low averages and 0% loss.\n- Localization:\n  - Not localized to a specific device/link; likely transient.\n- Likely root cause:\n  - Non-network transient (e.g., container CPU scheduling, background process jitter). Not indicative of persistent path or OSPF instability.\n\nService Access Observations\n- Load-balanced service (web99.local):\n  - HTTP GETs from host show total times ~1.0–1.2 s with TTFB ~0.2–0.4 s. Requests complete reliably; no 5 s timeouts were observed via the load balancer during testing.\n  - This suggests the load balancer is either avoiding the failed backend (web_server_1) or using other backends that respond promptly.\n- Direct backend access:\n  - web0, web2, web3 respond consistently with totals ~1.0–1.3 s and TTFB ~0.22–0.51 s.\n  - web1 consistently times out at ~5 s despite open TCP port, indicating application non-responsiveness.\n\nConclusions\n- The routed underlay and OSPF control-plane are healthy; routes and adjacencies are correct.\n- Primary issues are on the service/policy layer:\n  1) Policy/security anomaly: Backend web servers (web0–web3) are directly resolvable and reachable from access hosts, contrary to design intent. Fault localized to dns_server advertising these names to clients and lack of L3/L4 access controls on the server_access_router path.\n  2) Application outage on web_server_1: HTTP service is accepting connections but not responding, causing 5-second client timeouts and queued sockets. Network path to it is fine; failure is on the server/application.\n- Secondary/benign observations:\n  - HEAD returning 501 via the load balancer is due to upstream servers lacking HEAD support and is not a network fault.\n  - Transient ICMP RTT spikes appear non-persistent and likely due to host/container scheduling, not path instability.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 19330, "output_tokens": 5064, "total_tokens": 24394, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 18688}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3456}}}
